text: INTRODUCTION
label: HH1

text: This summary of industry and trade information addresses explosives, propellant powders,
label: BODY

text: and related items.  Data and information are presented for the period 1992 through 1996.  The
label: BODY

text: summary is organized into four main sections: U.S. industry profile, U.S. market, U.S. trade,
label: BODY

text: and foreign industry profile.  The U.S. industry profile section describes the industry
label: BODY

text: structure, manufacturing methods, and regulatory factors.  The U.S. market section provides
label: BODY

text: information on domestic consumption and production of these products and consumer
label: BODY

text: characteristics and factors affecting demand.  The segment on U.S. trade includes data on
label: BODY

text: U.S. import and export levels, the trade balance, principal suppliers, and U.S. and foreign
label: BODY

text: trade measures.  The foreign industry profile section provides information on major world
label: BODY

text: manufacturers of these products.  In addition, an appendix provides an explanation of current
label: BODY

text: tariff and trade agreements terms used in the Harmonized Tariff Schedule of the United States
label: BODY

text: (HTS).  The products and data covered herein do not include those products intended for use
label: BODY

text: by the U.S. military establishment.1
label: BODY

text: Domestic shipments of the products covered in this summary —  explosives, propellant
label: BODY

text: powders, and related items —  increased by about 12.8 percent2 from less than $1.5 billion in
label: BODY

text: 1992 to nearly $1.7 billion by the end of 1994.  After decreasing to about $1.6 billion in 1995,
label: BODY

text: sales rose to almost $1.8 billion in 1996.   This represents an average annual increase during
label: BODY

text: 1992-96 of about 4.9 percent.
label: BODY

text: All of the products covered in this summary are explosive or rapid-burning products that
label: BODY

text: utilize the heat, pressure, and/or light generated in their application to accomplish their desired
label: BODY

text: function.  These groupings encompass a wide variety of products, including prepared
label: BODY

text: explosives such as dynamite, trinitrotoluene (TNT), pentaerythritol tetranitrate (PETN),
label: BODY

text: azides, and other high explosives; propellant powders such as black powder, smokeless
label: BODY

text: powders, certain rocket fuels, and the like; fuses and detonators; fireworks; matches; signal
label: BODY

text: flares and other signaling devices; spark-producing metal alloys; and a number of other
label: BODY

text: pyrotechnic articles.  These products are manufactured using a variety of physical and
label: BODY

text: chemical processes incorporating a number of raw materials into the final product.  They are
label: BODY

text: principally used in commercial and industrial applications in mining, quarrying, well drilling,
label: BODY

text: construction and demolition industries, agriculture, and a number of metal working and
label: BODY

text: metallurgical applications.  In addition, many products (e.g., dynamite, smokeless powder,
label: BODY

text: black powder, fireworks, flares, signaling devices, cigarette lighter flints, matches, and many
label: BODY

text: others) are also used by private consumers.
label: BODY

text: Ammonium nitrate-fuel oil (ANFO) blasting agents3 represent the largest industrial explosive
label: BODY

text: manufactured (in terms of quantity) in the United States.  This product is used primarily in
label: BODY

text: 4 This product does produce a small amount of smoke.
label: BODY

text: mining and quarrying operations.  The components are generally mixed at or near the point
label: BODY

text: of use for safety reasons.  The mixed product is relatively safe and easily handled and can be
label: BODY

text: poured into drill holes in the mass or object to be blasted.
label: BODY

text: Dynamites and other prepared high explosives are also used in mining and quarrying
label: BODY

text: operations, as well as in construction, land clearing for agricultural use, and demolition
label: BODY

text: operations.  They are usually shipped packaged in a finished condition and do not require
label: BODY

text: additional mixing at the point of use.  They are generally safe to handle and ship when
label: BODY

text: reasonable care is taken to avoid exposure to excess heat or shock.  In use, a blasting cap,
label: BODY

text: electric detonator, or some other type of initiator is generally needed to fire these types of high
label: BODY

text: explosives.  The largest sources of U.S. imports of these products are Canada and Sweden,
label: BODY

text: while Saudi Arabia, Canada, and Venezuela are the principal markets for U.S. exports.
label: BODY

text: Propellant powders include principally smokeless powder and black powder.  Smokeless
label: BODY

text: powder4 is usually nitrocellulose with a nitrogen content of about 13.1 percent.  The
label: BODY

text: nitrocellulose is made into a dough using an alcohol-ether mixture.  Various plasticizers and
label: BODY

text: other modifiers are sometimes added in small amounts.  The product is primarily used in
label: BODY

text: ammunition for sporting rifles, pistols, and shotguns.  Some is also used in fireworks and
label: BODY

text: other pyrotechnic articles.  Black powder is a mixture of potassium nitrate, charcoal, and
label: BODY

text: sulfur.  It is used in black powder firearms and certain blasting operations.  The amount of
label: BODY

text: smoke produced is very high relative to that of smokeless powder.  The largest source of U.S.
label: BODY

text: imports of these products is Canada, while Israel, Canada, and Mexico are the main markets
label: BODY

text: for U.S. exports.
label: BODY

text: Fireworks are made using a variety of methods and each type is designed to produce specific
label: BODY

text: effects.  The effects are a combination of the light and/or sound produced by the combustion
label: BODY

text: of the explosive and various other ingredients.  The combustion is usually initiated by the
label: BODY

text: application of a heat source.  Fireworks accounted for the largest part of U.S. imports of
label: BODY

text: explosives materials (about 41 percent by value) in 1996.   Most of the U.S. imports of these
label: BODY

text: products (mainly fireworks) come from China.
label: BODY

text: Matches are pyrotechnic articles manufactured by coating one end of a paper or wooden stick
label: BODY

text: with a combustible compound consisting principally of phosphorus.  The compound is
label: BODY

text: designed to ignite when a certain level of heat is supplied by friction in the process of striking.
label: BODY

text: There are a variety of sizes and types of matches.  Wooden stemmed matches, used primarily
label: BODY

text: to light fires in fireplaces, stoves, etc., are packaged and sold in boxes or tubes.  Paper
label: BODY

text: stemmed matches are generally packaged in books.  Since the covers of these books are often
label: BODY

text: used as advertisements, many book matches are given away as promotional items.  The major
label: BODY

text: use of book matches is in the igniting of tobacco products.  Canada, Japan, and Sweden
label: BODY

text: supply the majority of U.S. imports of these products, while Canada is the destination for
label: BODY

text: most U.S. exports.

text: U.S. INDUSTRY PROFILE
label: HH1

text: Industry Structure
label: HH1

text: The raw materials, producer types, and principal consumers of the U.S. industry segment
label: BODY

text: which includes explosives, propellant powders, and related items are shown in figure 1.  The
label: BODY

text: products addressed in  this summary are classified in Standard Industrial Classification Code
label: BODY

text: (SIC) number 2892 - Explosives; parts of SIC numbers 2899 - Miscellaneous Chemicals and
label: BODY

text: Chemical Preparations, Not Elsewhere Classified; and 3999 - Miscellaneous Manufacturing
label: BODY

text: Industries, Not Elsewhere Classified.  These products are manufactured domestically by
label: BODY

text: approximately 100 firms which operate about 150 to 160 manufacturing facilities.  These
label: BODY

text: firms range from subsidiaries of large multinational conglomerates to small firms employing
label: BODY

text: only 1 to 3 persons.  Firms which employ 100 or fewer persons account for 75 to 85 percent
label: BODY

text: of the total number of firms in this industry, and firms which employ 20 or fewer persons
label: BODY

text: amount to about half.  Firms which manufacture explosives, propellant powders, and related
label: BODY

text: items are located in more than 30 states.  Texas, California, and Kentucky together contain
label: BODY

text: about 40 of these firms.
label: BODY

text: About 32 U.S. companies reported domestic production of industrial explosives and blasting
label: BODY

text: agents to the U.S. Department of the Interior's U.S. Geological Survey5 during 1996.  These
label: BODY

text: firms manufacture dynamite and other prepared explosives, explosive water-based products
label: BODY

text: (gels, slurries, and emulsions), and blasting agents based on ammonium nitrate and fuel oil.
label: BODY

text: Approximately 25 other domestic companies manufacture fireworks.  The rest of the firms in
label: BODY

text: this industry, as well as some of those that primarily make industrial explosives or fireworks,
label: BODY

text: manufacture initiating devices (e.g., blasting caps, fuses) and various other pyrotechnic and
label: BODY

text: pyrophoric products (e.g., flares, rain rockets, matches).
label: BODY

text: Industry analysts indicate that this industry, for the most part, is not highly integrated.  The
label: BODY

text: companies buy most of the input materials used in the manufacture of their products from
label: BODY

text: non-related sources.  These companies generally market their products directly to the final
label: BODY

text: consumer or to distributors who sell to the final consumer, although there are some products
label: BODY

text: (e.g., fireworks, flares, black powder) which can pass through several layers of distribution
label: BODY

text: before reaching the final consumer.  The products of this industry are usually sold on a bid
label: BODY

text: or spot basis.  Although annual or longer-term contracts are not unknown in this industry,
label: BODY

text: such contracts tend not to be the norm.6

text: Transportation restrictions on these products, particularly on waterborne shipments, have
label: BODY

text: resulted in a large number of firms in this industry being located in many countries.  The
label: BODY

text: companies that make up the U.S. industry generally market their products domestically within
label: BODY

text: specific geographic areas.  These companies, most of which are locally owned, tend to serve
label: BODY

text: consumers in their local geographic region.  However, significant levels of international trade
label: BODY

text: do exist (i.e., about 15 to 20 percent of domestic production is exported in any given year) and
label: BODY

text: certain products are shipped significant distances.  U.S. imports are generally sold by
label: BODY

text: domestic producers who want to broaden their product lines or by distributors who may
label: BODY

text: market both domestic and imported products.  A significant number of U.S. firms are partially
label: BODY

text: or completely owned or controlled by foreign firms, and there is at least a moderate level of
label: BODY

text: U.S. ownership of foreign firms, although specific information concerning the extent of such
label: BODY

text: cross-ownership is not available.

text: The estimated total employment in this industry is in the range of 13,000 to 14,000 people,
label: BODY

text: about two-thirds of whom are production workers.7  The skill level of these production
label: BODY

text: workers is considered by industry analysts8 to be moderate and, overall, this industry is
label: BODY

text: considered to be labor intensive.  During 1992-96, the output per production worker hour
label: BODY

text: (productivity) is estimated to have increased slightly.  Wage rates for production workers in
label: BODY

text: this industry are estimated by industry analysts9 to have increased by about 3 to 5 percent
label: BODY

text: annually during the same period, from estimated average hourly earnings of about $14.12 in
label: BODY

text: 1992 to about $16.71 in 1996.  Many of the production workers in this industry are employed
label: BODY

text: on a seasonal basis, particularly those workers employed in the manufacture of certain
label: BODY

text: fireworks.  Payroll is estimated by industry observers10 to amount to about 27 to 30 percent
label: BODY

text: of the value of shipments; raw material costs are estimated to account for about 32 to 36
label: BODY

text: percent of sales; other production costs, general administrative and selling expenses, and
label: BODY

text: profits account for the remainder.

text: Manufacturing Methods
label: HH2

text: The explosives, propellant powders, initiating devices, fireworks, and other pyrotechnic
label: BODY

text: products that are described in this summary are manufactured utilizing a variety of chemical
label: BODY

text: reactions in facilities ranging in operations from complex automated processes to relatively
label: BODY

text: simple mixing of ingredients at the point of use.  While there are a large number of ingredients
label: BODY

text: that could be used to manufacture the products this summary covers, many of them are either
label: BODY

text: too sensitive to meet safe handling requirements during production, storage, and shipment, or
label: BODY

text: they are too expensive to permit use in the manufacture of a cost-competitive product.
label: BODY

text: Therefore, the majority of the products that are covered here are manufactured from a fairly
label: BODY

text: small number of time-tested and proven materials using well-known and understood processes
label: BODY

text: and methods.  These ingredients are used in processes that are rigidly controlled to produce
label: BODY

text: a quality product in a safe production environment.  As a result, the safety record for
label: BODY

text: production workers in this industry compares favorably with that of most chemical industry
label: BODY

text: manufacturing operations.

text: Regulatory Factors
label: HH2

text: U.S. producers of the products covered in this summary are privately operated, but are subject
label: BODY

text: to a large number of Government regulations under various statutes designed to protect and
label: BODY

text: improve health, safety, and the environment.  These regulations influence the industry
label: BODY

text: processes and production costs, and thus affect business operations and investment decisions.
label: BODY

text: Most research and development funds are directed either toward cost-cutting or toward
label: BODY

text: regulatory compliance.  This industry must meet many stringent standards and regulations for
label: BODY

text: health and safety for every facet of the manufacturing, handling, shipping, and storage of these
label: BODY

text: products.  The members of the industry state that they work very closely, both individually
label: BODY

text: and through various trade associations, with local, State, and Federal Government agencies
label: BODY

text: to ensure the safe manufacture and use of these materials.  The principal Federal agencies that
label: BODY

text: regulate this industry include the Occupational Safety and Health Administration, the U.S.
label: BODY

text: Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, and Firearms, the U.S. Department of Transportation, the
label: BODY

text: Environmental Protection Agency, and the Consumer Products Safety Commission. According
label: BODY

text: to industry trade associations, various State and local governments also impose regulations.
label: BODY

text: Examples of Federal laws related to environmental hazards that apply to this industry include
label: BODY

text: the Emergency Planning and Community Right-to-Know Act, the Clean Air Act, the Resource
label: BODY

text: Conservation and Recovery Act, and the Superfund legislation.11
label: BODY

text: U.S. MARKET
label: HH1

text: Consumer Characteristics and Factors Affecting Demand12
label: HH2

text: The principal consumers are the mining (particularly coal mining) industries, quarrying
label: BODY

text: operations, construction firms, and civilian munitions industries.13  Together these markets
label: BODY

text: consume more than 75 percent of all the products of the explosives, propellant powders, and
label: BODY

text: related items industry segment covered in this summary.  Other markets for these products
label: BODY

text: include the agriculture industry and the general public.  The markets for these products are
label: BODY

text: nationwide, although the majority of the explosives and related items covered herein are used
label: BODY

text: in various mining operations (particularly coal mining operations) in both the eastern and
label: BODY

text: western mountain regions.14
label: BODY

text: The domestic consumers of most explosives, propellant powders, and related items are
label: BODY

text: commercial companies (e.g., mines, quarries, construction companies) which use these
label: BODY

text: products in their business operations.  The domestic demand for these products is principally
label: BODY

text: derived from the demand for the mined or quarried raw materials used in power generation
label: BODY

text: (coal) and a wide variety of downstream industrial and consumer products (e.g., metals,
label: BODY

text: pigments, gems, gravel).  U.S. industrial demand generally tracks the trends exhibited by the
label: BODY

text: general economy.  It is most strongly affected by changes in demand for electrical power and
label: BODY

text: construction.  In addition, some products (e.g., fireworks, black powder) are sold directly to
label: BODY

text: private individuals for such things as stump and rock removal in connection with land
label: BODY

text: clearing, holiday celebrations, revolutionary war, civil war, and other war battle reenactments,
label: BODY

text: hunting, and other forms of recreational activities.  According to industry analysts, the overall
label: BODY

text: level of demand in this market segment is most affected by changes in the level of disposable
label: BODY

text: income available to the general public.
label: BODY

text: Consumption
label: HH2

text: The overall trend for U.S. apparent consumption of explosives, propellant powders, and
label: BODY

text: related items was generally upward at an estimated average annual rate of about 3 percent
label: BODY

text: from less than $1.5 billion in 1992 to over 1.6 billion in 1996 (table 1 and figure 2).  Demand
label: BODY

text: for these products reflected the average growth trend of the U.S. economy during that period.

text: The value of U.S. apparent consumption in 1992 was the lowest during the five-year period
label: BODY

text: under discussion.  This value, however, despite being about 24 percent lower than the
label: BODY

text: previous year, reflects traditional market levels.  In 1991, U.S. apparent consumption of
label: BODY

text: explosives, propellant powders, and related items grew significantly, primarily because of an
label: BODY

text: increase in coal mining in response to the Persian Gulf War in that year.  As the cost of crude
label: BODY

text: petroleum increased during the Persian Gulf War, many consumers switched from petroleum
label: BODY

text: to coal for fuel and power generation.  The resulting increased demand for coal and coal
label: BODY

text: products fueled a corresponding increase in demand for explosives and related items by the
label: BODY

text: coal industry.  In addition, because ANFO-based blasting mixtures represent approximately
label: BODY

text: 98 percent, by weight, of total domestic consumption of all industrial explosives,15 and the
label: BODY

text: price of the fuel oil consumed in the manufacture of these products increased, the price of
label: BODY

text: these products also increased.  During 1992, several months after the Gulf War ended, the
label: BODY

text: market prices of crude petroleum on the world market stabilized and declined somewhat, and
label: BODY

text: the concern about the security and stability of the crude petroleum supply from the Persian
label: BODY

text: Gulf region abated.  As a result, coal production in the U.S. fields fell back closer to their
label: BODY

text: normal levels in 1992, and, in response to these market forces, so did domestic demand for the
label: BODY

text: types of explosives and related items used by that industry.16
label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: The market share of U.S. apparent consumption in U.S. dollars accounted for by imports of
label: BODY

text: explosives, propellant powders, and related items during the period covered by this summary
label: BODY

text: ranged from approximately 12 percent to 15 percent,17 which is consistent with general
label: BODY

text: historical trends for such imports in this industry.18  The major products imported into the
label: BODY

text: United States are fireworks, propellant powders, and detonating devices.  The imported
label: BODY

text: products tend to be slightly lower priced than the equivalent domestic products.  According
label: BODY

text: to industry analysts, in general, there appears to be relatively little difference between many
label: BODY

text: of the imported and domestic products with respect to the quality, performance, availability,
label: BODY

text: or any of the variety of other characteristics which can affect demand in the domestic
label: BODY

text: marketplace.
label: BODY

text: Production
label: HH2

text: The general trends and overall levels of the value of domestic production of explosives,
label: BODY

text: propellant powders, and related items follow closely those of U.S. apparent consumption.
label: BODY

text: These levels are shown in table 1 and figure 2.  There are always major concerns for safety
label: BODY

text: where large amounts of explosives, propellant powders, and related items are stored, and
label: BODY

text: many of these products have relatively short shelf lives.  Consequently, manufacturers'
label: BODY

text: inventories of these products tend not to be large and the levels tend to remain relatively
label: BODY

text: constant; as a result, the values shown for U.S. production levels tend to be very similar to the
label: BODY

text: values shown for domestic shipments.  Shipments of explosives, propellant powders, and
label: BODY

text: related items increased by about 20.6 percent from less than $1.5 billion in 1992 to nearly
label: BODY

text: $1.8 billion in 1996, representing an estimated average annual rate of growth in the range of
label: BODY

text: about 4.9 percent.  Overall, the factors affecting the values and trends of domestic production
label: BODY

text: of explosives, propellant powders, and related items during the period covered by this
label: BODY

text: summary are very similar to those previously discussed that affected the values and trends of
label: BODY

text: domestic apparent consumption.
label: BODY

text: U.S. TRADE
label: HH1

text: Overview
label: HH2

text: Table 2 shows the U.S. trade and trade balances for those countries and country groups with
label: BODY

text: the largest volume of two-way trade in the subject commodities during 1992-96.  Overall,
label: BODY

text: except for 1992, the United States had a positive trade balance in explosives, propellant
label: BODY

text: powders, and related items during 1992-96.  During 1992, the U.S. trade balance for these
label: BODY

text: products was slightly negative reflecting relatively high imports from Canada compared with
label: BODY

text: the rest of the period.  In 1993-96, substantial positive trade balances were recorded as a
label: BODY

text: result of growing U.S. exports to Canada and Saudi Arabia and declining imports from
label: BODY

text: Canada.  During 1992-96, on an overall basis, Canada was the most important U.S. partner
label: BODY

text: in international trade of these products, accounting for the largest share of U.S. exports, as
label: BODY

text: well as being the second largest supplier of U.S. imports.  Canada has eliminated its duties
label: BODY

text: on U.S. origin imports of these products under the North American Free Trade Agreement.
label: BODY

text: Japan, the European Union (particularly the United Kingdom and Italy), and Australia are
label: BODY

text: other major markets for U.S. exports of these products.  These trading partners all have
label: BODY

text: relatively higher rates of duty for imports of these products than the United States.  The 1996
label: BODY

text: rates of duty assessed on these products for the United States’ major trading partners are
label: BODY

text: shown in table 3.
label: BODY

text: U.S. Imports
label: HH2

text: Principal Suppliers and Import Levels
label: BODY

text: U.S. imports of explosives, propellant powders, and related items declined from about $216
label: BODY

text: million in 1992 to about $187 million in 1995.  Industry analysts indicate that this decline was
label: BODY

text: principally caused by decreased imports from Canada which resulted from the increased
label: BODY

text: allocation of production by some Canadian manufacturers to meet more of local demand.
label: BODY

text: Total U.S. imports of these products then increased to about $208 million in 1996 (table 4).
label: BODY

text: The increase was mainly the result of increased imports of fireworks from China and Mexico.
label: BODY

text: China is the major source of U.S. imports of these products, accounting for about 45 percent
label: BODY

text: in 1996.  The majority of the explosives, propellant powders, and related items that the United
label: BODY

text: States imports from China are classified as fireworks.  Table 4 ranks U.S. imports of these
label: BODY

text: products by principal source, based on the value of 1996 imports.

text: Tariff and nontariff measures19

text: Table 3 shows the rates of duty, as of January 1, 1997, applicable to imports of explosives,
label: BODY

label: BODY

text: States (HTS).  Column 1-general rates of duty for countries considered for most-favored-
label: BODY

text: nation (MFN) treatment range from zero to 6.9 percent ad valorem on imports of these
label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: U.S. Government trade-related investigations
label: BODY

text: The U.S. International Trade Commission has conducted one investigation on a product
label: BODY

text: covered by this summary during the last several years.  In June 1991, the Commission made
label: BODY

text: an affirmative final determination under the U.S. antidumping law with respect to imports of
label: BODY

text: sparklers (a type of fireworks) from China.21  This affirmative determination followed
label: BODY

text: notification by the U.S. Department of Commerce (Commerce) that it had found that such
label: BODY

text: sparklers imported from China were being sold in the United States at less than fair value.22
label: BODY

text: As a result of the Commission's affirmative determination, Commerce issued an antidumping
label: BODY

text: order covering sparklers imported from China.  Under the order, imports of sparklers from
label: BODY

text: Chinese firms are assessed additional duties, the amount of which is based on Commerce’s
label: BODY

text: calculated margins of unfair underselling.  The Chinese firm of Guangxi Native Produce
label: BODY

text: Import and Export Company was subject to an antidumping duty of 41.75 percent ad valorem
label: BODY

text: in addition to the regular "General" rate of duty charged on imports of these products.  U.S.
label: BODY

text: imports of sparklers from all other Chinese manufacturers of fireworks were subject to an
label: BODY

text: antidumping duty of 93.54 percent ad valorem in addition to the regular "General" rate of duty
label: BODY

text: charged on U.S. imports of these products.23  The most recent U.S. Department of Commerce
label: BODY

text: review of the order was undertaken beginning in late 1994.  On July 30, 1996, the U.S.
label: BODY

text: Department of Commerce announced that it had determined the country-wide dumping margin
label: BODY

text: to be 93.54 percent, including imports of sparklers from Guangxi Native Produce Import and
label: BODY

text: Export Company.24

text: Most industrialized countries have the ability to make most of the explosives, propellant
label: BODY

text: powders, and related items that can be made by U.S. manufacturers and are generally able to
label: BODY

text: meet their domestic demand.  The major competitors of U.S. firms in the global market are
label: BODY

text: companies located in Canada, China, Japan, and  the European Union (EU).  According to
label: BODY

text: industry analysts, these countries have industries that have developed to a level similar to that
label: BODY

text: of the United States in terms of capital, research and development, production technology, raw
label: BODY

text: material and labor availability, product variety, and marketing ability.  In addition, the levels
label: BODY

text: of both horizontal and vertical integration of foreign firms in the industrialized countries are
label: BODY

text: similar to those of companies located in the United States.26  In the less industrialized countries
label: BODY

text: the range of products available tends to be smaller and usually contains less of the higher-
label: BODY

text: valued high-tech products.  Currently, many countries (e.g., China, Mexico) have some
label: BODY

text: advantage in the area of labor costs, and according to industry analysts, most countries have
label: BODY

text: somewhat less rigorous environmental laws than does the United States.27

text: In the Harmonized Tariff Schedule of the United States (HTS), chapters 1 through 97 cover
label: BODY

text: all goods in trade and incorporate in the tariff nomenclature the internationally adopted
label: BODY

text: Harmonized Commodity Description and Coding System through the 6-digit level of product
label: BODY

text: description.  Subordinate 8-digit product subdivisions, either enacted by Congress or
label: BODY

text: proclaimed by the President, allow more narrowly applicable duty rates; 10-digit
label: BODY

text: administrative statistical reporting numbers provide data of national interest.  Chapters 98 and
label: BODY

text: 99 contain special U.S. classifications and temporary rate provisions, respectively.  The HTS
label: BODY

text: replaced the Tariff Schedules of the United States (TSUS) effective January 1, 1989.
label: BODY

text: Duty rates in the general subcolumn of HTS column 1 are most-favored-nation (MFN) rates,
label: BODY

text: many of which have been eliminated or are being reduced as concessions resulting from the
label: BODY

text: Uruguay Round of Multilateral Trade Negotiations.  Column 1-general duty rates apply to
label: BODY

text: all countries except those enumerated in HTS general note 3(b) (Afghanistan, Cuba, Laos,
label: BODY

text: North Korea, and Vietnam), which are subject to the statutory rates set forth in column 2.
label: BODY

text: Specified goods from designated MFN-eligible countries may be eligible for reduced rates of
label: BODY

text: duty or for duty-free entry under one or more preferential tariff programs.  Such tariff
label: BODY

text: treatment is set forth in the special subcolumn of HTS rate of duty column 1 or in the general
label: BODY

text: notes.  If eligibility for special tariff rates is not claimed or established, goods are dutiable at
label: BODY

text: column 1-general rates.  The HTS does not enumerate those countries as to which a total or
label: BODY

text: partial embargo has been declared.
label: BODY

text: The Generalized System of Preferences (GSP) affords nonreciprocal tariff preferences to
label: BODY

text: developing countries to aid their economic development and to diversify and expand their
label: BODY

text: production and exports.  The U.S. GSP, enacted in title V of the Trade Act of 1974 for 10
label: BODY

text: years and extended several times thereafter, applies to merchandise imported on or after
label: BODY

text: January 1, 1976 and before the close of June 30, 1998.  Indicated by the symbol "A", "A*",
label: BODY

text: or "A+" in the special subcolumn, the GSP provides duty-free entry to eligible articles the
label: BODY

text: product of and imported directly from designated beneficiary developing countries, as set forth
label: BODY

text: in general note 4 to the HTS.
label: BODY

text: The Caribbean Basin Economic Recovery Act (CBERA) affords nonreciprocal tariff
label: BODY

text: preferences to developing countries in the Caribbean Basin area to aid their economic
label: BODY

text: development and to diversify and expand their production and exports.  The CBERA, enacted
label: BODY

text: in title II of Public Law 98-67, implemented by Presidential Proclamation 5133 of November
label: BODY

text: 30, 1983, and amended by the Customs and Trade Act of 1990, applies to merchandise
label: BODY

text: entered, or withdrawn from warehouse for consumption, on or after January 1, 1984.
label: BODY

text: Indicated by the symbol "E" or "E*" in the special subcolumn, the CBERA provides duty-free
label: BODY

text: entry to eligible articles, and reduced-duty treatment to certain other articles, which are the
label: BODY

text: product of and imported directly from designated countries, as set forth in general note
label: BODY

text: 7 to
label: BODY

text: the HTS.
label: BODY

text: Free rates of duty in the special subcolumn followed by the symbol "IL" are applicable to
label: BODY

text: products of Israel under the United States-Israel Free Trade Area Implementation Act of
label: BODY

text: 1985 (IFTA), as provided in general note 8 to the HTS.
label: BODY

text: Preferential nonreciprocal duty-free or reduced-duty treatment in the special subcolumn
label: BODY

text: followed by the symbol "J" or "J*" in parentheses is afforded to eligible articles the product
label: BODY

text: of designated beneficiary countries under the Andean Trade Preference Act (ATPA), enacted
label: BODY

text: as title II of Public Law 102-182 and implemented by Presidential Proclamation 6455 of July
label: BODY

text: 2, 1992 (effective July 22, 1992), as set forth in general note 11 to the HTS.
label: BODY

text: Preferential or free rates of duty in the special subcolumn followed by the symbol "CA" are
label: BODY

text: applicable to eligible goods of Canada, and rates followed by the symbol "MX" are applicable
label: BODY

text: to eligible goods of Mexico, under the North American Free Trade Agreement, as provided
label: BODY

text: in general note 12 to the HTS and implemented effective January 1, 1994 by Presidential
label: BODY

text: Proclamation 6641 of December 15, 1993.  Goods must originate in the NAFTA region under
label: BODY

text: rules set forth in general note 12(t) and meet other requirements of the note and applicable
label: BODY

text: regulations.
label: BODY

text: Other special tariff treatment applies to particular products of insular possessions (general
label: BODY

text: note 3(a)(iv)), products of the West Bank and Gaza Strip (general note 3(a)(v)), goods
label: BODY

text: covered by the Automotive Products Trade Act (APTA) (general note 5) and the Agreement
label: BODY

text: on Trade in Civil Aircraft (ATCA) (general note 6), articles imported from freely
label: BODY

text: The General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade 1994 (GATT 1994), pursuant to the
label: BODY

text: Agreement Establishing the World Trade Organization, is based upon the earlier GATT 1947
label: BODY

text: (61 Stat. (pt. 5) A58; 8 UST (pt. 2) 1786) as the primary multilateral system of disciplines
label: BODY

text: and principles governing international trade.  Signatories' obligations under both the 1994 and
label: BODY

text: 1947 agreements focus upon most-favored-nation treatment, the maintenance of scheduled
label: BODY

text: concession rates of duty, and national treatment for imported products; the GATT also
label: BODY

text: provides the legal framework for customs valuation standards, "escape clause" (emergency)
label: BODY

text: actions, antidumping and countervailing duties, dispute settlement, and other measures.  The
label: BODY

text: results of the Uruguay Round of multilateral tariff negotiations are set forth by way of
label: BODY

text: separate schedules of concessions for each participating contracting party, with the U.S.
label: BODY

text: schedule designated as Schedule XX.
label: BODY

text: Pursuant to the Agreement on Textiles and Clothing (ATC) of the GATT 1994, member
label: BODY

text: countries are phasing out restrictions on imports under the prior "Arrangement Regarding
label: BODY

text: International Trade in Textiles" (known as the Multifiber Arrangement (MFA)).  Under the
label: BODY

text: MFA, which was a departure from GATT 1947 provisions, importing and exporting countries
label: BODY

text: negotiated bilateral agreements limiting textile and apparel shipments, and importing countries
label: BODY

text: could take unilateral action in the absence or violation of an agreement.  Quantitative limits
label: BODY

text: had been established on imported textiles and apparel of cotton, other vegetable fibers, wool,
label: BODY

text: man-made fibers or silk blends in an effort to prevent or limit market
label: BODY

text: disruption in the importing countries.  The ATC establishes notification and safeguard
label: BODY

text: procedures, along with other rules concerning the customs treatment of textile and apparel
label: BODY

text: shipments, and calls for the eventual complete integration of this sector into the GATT 1994
label: BODY

text: over a ten-year period, or by Jan. 1, 2005.
